page.title: 10Ecology of Horse-Eye Level
page.content: Horse-Eye Level is of great interest from an ecology point of view. It is mainly grazing meadows intersected with fresh water dykes. High water levels in winter attract large numbers of wildfowl. The area comes under Sussex Trust for Nature Conservation & is also a Bird Protection Area. As well as the Yellow Wagtail which is an important breeding species, other birdlife found in the area includes Swans, Herons, Seagulls, Crows, Lapwings, Partridge, Sparrows, Redshank & Snipe. Other wildlife inhabiting these levels include Otters, Mink, Frogs, Molluscs, Butterflies, Dragonfly, Perch, Roach and Rud. Sussex is now the main British stronghold of the Dragonfly - latin name Brachytron Pratense - and Horse-Eye Level is one of the two most important sites in the county.
